Answer: A liquidity pool is a pool of tokens that is locked in a smart contract and used to facilitate transactions on a decentralized exchange (DEX). Liquidity providers deposit equal value amounts of two different tokens into the pool, and they receive liquidity provider (LP) tokens in return that represent their share of the pool. Traders can then buy and sell tokens on the DEX, and their trades are executed against the reserves in the liquidity pool. LPs earn a proportionate share of the trading fees generated by the DEX, and they can withdraw their share of the tokens from the pool at any time.
